Maryland man's pandemic project: Fixing up bicycles and giving them away
SavedRead AloudShare
Print
A photo of a man sitting at a table with tools in front of him and a bike hanging behind him.
Image 1. Manuel Vera in the backyard of his home in Silver Spring, Maryland, on April 2021. Photo: John Kelly/Washington Post
By Washington Post, adapted by Newsela staff
Published:05/14/2021
Word Count:234
Manuel Vera is 71 years old. He lives in Maryland. He realized that homes must be full of old bikes. Children outgrow them. Some people stop riding them. He wanted to get these old bikes back on the road.

In 2020, he sent a message to his neighbors. It said he would fix their bikes for free.

Mr. Vera fixed 104 bicycles in the last year. He ran out of bikes to work on. In November he sent another note around. He asked if people had unused bikes. He would fix them up and give them away.

Mr. Vera gives the bikes away at a park. He says it is the perfect place.

A photo of a man standing next to a bike that is hanging up.
Image 2. Manuel Vera has fixed up 102 bicycles in the past year in his backyard. Photo: John Kelly/Washington Post
Memories Of Learning To Ride A Bike

Most of the neighbors are working-class people. Many are immigrants. An immigrant is someone who moves to a new country.

Bikes can be expensive. Many people cannot pay for one. Still, everyone should have a bike, he said.

Sometimes, Mr. Vera will see a bicycle he fixed. It makes him think about his boyhood. He grew up in Peru. His father taught him to ride. He remembers when his father first let go of the bike.

It was a surprise to ride by himself. He could go wherever his bike might take him.
