Hawai'i: The view from the crow's nest
SavedRead AloudShare
Print
This is a photograph of women and young girls  on the island of Hawaii performing a traditional hula dance.
Image 1. Women and girls in Hawaii performing a traditional hula dance. Hula is one of the surviving traditions of the Polynesian people, who first settled Hawaii more than 1,000 years ago. Photo: Ron Ardis/Wikimedia Commons
By Cricket Media, adapted by Newsela staff
Published:05/03/2021
Word Count:416
The Polynesian people were explorers. They sailed all over the South Pacific Ocean. Polynesians did not use compasses to travel. Instead, they studied the winds and stars. They tracked ocean currents and the paths of migratory birds.

Polynesia is in the South Pacific Ocean. It is a collection of more than  1,000 islands.

Polynesians traveled in voyaging canoes. They brought plants for their new home. One important plant was taro. Taro is a root vegetable. It is similar to a potato. The Polynesians also brought pigs, chickens and dogs.

The First Hawaiian People

Polynesians arrived in Hawai'i about 1,500 years ago. They were the first people on the islands. In time they became Native Hawaiians.

Native Hawaiians are also called ʻŌiwi.

Early Native Hawaiians farmed, hunted and gathered food. Taro was an important crop. It was cooked and mashed into a paste. This food is known as poi. Poi was an important part of Hawaiian diets.

This is a black and white photograph of a young boy and girl belonging to the Native Hawaiian community.Zoom-in
Image 2. Native Hawaiian children in 1900 photographed by Henry Wether Henshaw. Photo: Henry Wetherbee Henshaw/Wikimedia Commons.
believed that gods were all around in nature. Priests were known as kahuna. The priests managed temples. They also made sure people obeyed kapu.

Kapu was a set of rules. These were rules for life in early Hawai'i. For example, men and women could not eat together.

Ships Brought Explorers, Goods And Trouble

Native Hawaiians enjoyed many activities. These included surfing, boxing and wrestling.

But in 1778, life changed for the ʻŌiwi. Captain James Cook was an English explorer. He arrived on the islands with ships. Soon, other Europeans and Americans followed.

Europeans brought many changes to Hawai'i. They introduced their religion and their ways of government. Traders and ships brought goods from faraway places. They also brought diseases. These diseases caused thousands of Native Hawaiians to die.

Hawai'i Becomes A U.S. State

Honolulu is a city on the island of O'ahu. By the late 1800s, Honolulu became the main harbor. Ships arrived from all over the world.

Sugar is a major crop for Hawai'i. American businessmen owned many large sugarcane farms there. These Americans wanted to control the government. In 1891, Americans took control of the islands. Seven years later, Hawai'i joined the United States as a territory. It became the 50th state in 1959.

Polynesian traditions are still a part of island life. Hawaiian words are used in everyday language. Flower leis and hula dances are also Polynesian traditions. Today, they are found all over the Hawaiian islands.
